export const AI_CONTEXT = "You are an expert on Salesforce Salesforce Education Cloud (EDUCATIONCLOUD) Spring '26.\nAnswer questions based ONLY on the following product knowledge. If the question is not about EDUCATIONCLOUD or you are unsure, say so clearly. Keep answers concise (2-4 sentences).\nWhen mentioning domains or components, include markdown links using the URLs from the Links section below.\n\n## Domains (14)\n- **Recruitment** (recruitment): Manages the top of the enrollment funnel, from first inquiry to application-ready prospect.\n- **Admissions** (admissions): Handles the full application lifecycle from submission through document collection, review, and admission decisions.\n- **Academic Operations** (academics): The structural backbone that defines what an institution offers: programs, courses, academic terms, and learning objectives.\n- **Enrollment** (enrollment): Tracks a student's active participation in programs and courses, from initial program enrollment through course registration, grade recording, and achievement recognition.\n- **Student Records** (records): The central person data domain that anchors every other part of Education Cloud.\n- **Student Success** (success): Empowers advisors and students to track competencies, personal traits, career interests, and academic progress toward degree completion.\n- **Student Financials** (financials): Manages tuition, fees, financial aid, and student account balances through the Salesforce pricing and order engine adapted for higher education.\n- **Mentoring** (mentoring): Manages structured mentoring programs that pair students with mentors for academic guidance, career coaching, and personal development.\n- **Alumni & Advancement** (alumni): Engages alumni through lifetime relationship management, gift tracking, pledge fulfillment, and volunteer coordination.\n- **Appointments** (appointments): Provides centralized self-service appointment scheduling for advising, tutoring, financial aid counseling, and administrative meetings.\n- **Education Analytics** (analytics): Delivers institutional insights through CRM Analytics dashboards covering recruitment yield, enrollment trends, retention rates, student success metrics, and financial health.\n- **Agentforce** (agentforce): Deploys AI-powered agents across the student lifecycle to automate communication, answer questions, and surface actionable insights.\n- **Experience Cloud** (experience): Powers learner-facing self-service portals for application tracking, course registration, financial account management, and alumni community engagement.\n- **Data 360** (data360): Consolidates student data from disparate legacy systems into a unified, deduplicated view using Salesforce Data 360 capabilities.\n\n## Key Components (68)\n- **Prospect Management** [Recruitment]: Captures and tracks prospective students from initial inquiry through application readiness. Education Cloud uses the lead and person account objects to record suspect and prospect information. When a prospect signals interest in your institution, a person account is created with their details so that the recruiting team can better engage with the potential student. Suspects who have not yet indicated interest are tracked as leads, and when they express interest, they are automatically converted to person accounts through lead conversion.\n- **Campaign Management** [Recruitment]: Orchestrates multi-channel recruitment campaigns targeting specific student populations. The Recruitment and Admissions app enables admissions officers and recruiters to stay on top of their tasks while monitoring the overall health of the admissions pipeline in real time. Actionable Lists allow directors to create prospect lists from multiple objects, collaborate with staff, and take action within the list. These lists can be assigned to recruiters for targeted follow-up based on specific criteria such as geography, academic interest, or engagement level.\n- **Recruitment Events** [Recruitment]: Manages campus tours, open houses, information sessions, and virtual recruitment events. Campus and Program Finder makes information about your campus, learning programs, and support programs publicly searchable on your Experience Cloud site. It helps applicants, students, and families browse and search for campuses, schools, and programs in their area. They can filter by learning program, campus or school, grade level, and other criteria, with search results presented in a list or on a map.\n- **Recruitment Communications** [Recruitment]: Manages outbound communications to prospective students across email, SMS, and direct mail channels. Education Cloud's inquiry management flows provide multiple channels for prospects to engage with your institution. The Sign Up for Information flow processes requests to receive regular updates and can enroll prospects in Marketing Cloud journeys using Marketing Cloud Connect. The Connect With Us flow creates contact request records linking prospects with staff, while the Submit an Inquiry Form flow creates case records for detailed questions.\n- **Territory Management** [Recruitment]: Assigns recruitment counselors to geographic territories, feeder schools, and prospect segments. Actionable List Engagement, Actionable Segmentation, and Actionable List Member allow directors to create lists from multiple objects, collaborate with other staff, and take action within the list. Use cases include prioritizing applicants, creating lists of students based on specific criteria, creating portfolios of prospects for relationship officers, and curating lists of VIP parents to call based on defined criteria.\n- **Application Management** [Admissions]: Manages the creation, submission, and lifecycle of student applications. Education Cloud uses OmniStudio components to create customizable application forms. When an applicant registers on the learner portal, Education Cloud automatically creates a person account for them. The platform supports multiple application types with configurable stages, and applications progress through statuses from draft through submitted, under review, and decision rendered. Multi-cycle support allows the same applicant to apply across different programs or terms.\n- **Document Tracking** [Admissions]: Manages the collection and verification of required application documents including transcripts, test scores, recommendation letters, essays, and financial documents. Education Cloud provides multiple components for managing documents including Document Checklist for tracking required materials, Document Generation for creating standardized correspondence, and Intelligent Document Reader for automated document processing. These tools reduce friction and streamline updates between students and staff by enabling real-time document uploading and automated document management processes.\n- **Application Review** [Admissions]: Routes applications through structured review workflows with configurable reviewer assignments, scoring rubrics, and decision criteria. The Reviewer Console is designed specifically for people who conduct application reviews. Reviewers can be anyone in your institution or external partners, and they receive the Education Cloud Limited Access permission set license giving them access to the elements needed to view and approve applications. The console shows a list of assigned applications, tasks due today, and upcoming events.\n- **Admissions Decisions** [Admissions]: Records and communicates admission decisions including accept, deny, waitlist, and conditional admission. Application decision records represent the publicly released decision for an application to an institution. These records are automatically shared with Experience Cloud users on the decision release date and early application release date defined on the application timeline object. If no decision release date is entered, records are not shared with portal users, and if the date is in the past, records are shared immediately.\n- **Preliminary Applications** [Admissions]: Supports early-stage or simplified application forms that capture initial interest before a full application is required. Preliminary Application Reference records store applications that are in progress, allowing applicants to start an application and return to complete it later. This supports multi-stage application workflows where different sections can be completed at different times. For example, an applicant might submit basic personal information today and come back a week later to enter their educational history, without needing to complete stages in a linear order.\n- **Admissions Console** [Admissions]: A purpose-built staff workspace that surfaces the most important admissions data in a single view. The Admissions Console is built using Lightning App Builder and includes an Education Analytics Dashboard component showing Recruitment and Admissions Insights, tabbed list views for applications ready for decision and assigned reviews, a Today's Tasks component, and an upcoming events list. The console can be customized to suit the requirements of your institution with role-specific layouts.\n- **Program Management** [Academic Operations]: Defines degree programs, certificates, and academic pathways with their requirements, credit thresholds, and learning outcomes. Learning programs can be degree or credential programs, academic support programs, recreational programs, or continuing education. Education Cloud uses the same architectural building blocks to model each of them, with Learning representing the curriculum, Learning Achievement capturing the outcome, and Learning Program Plan detailing the specific requirements for a given catalog year. When the institution finalizes its catalog for the next academic year, changed requirements are captured in a new program plan record.\n- **Course Management** [Academic Operations]: Maintains the institutional course catalog with course descriptions, credit values, prerequisites, and corequisites. Modeling courses in Education Cloud relies on the Learning object, which represents information about a curriculum that can be made available as a course, program, or on-site experience. When you create a new learning record, you designate whether it is represented as a learning program or learning course. The Learning Course object then stores detailed information about a specific course within the larger learning framework.\n- **Course Offerings** [Academic Operations]: Schedules courses for specific academic terms with assigned instructors, meeting times, locations, and enrollment capacity. A course offering record provides specific details including the academic session, faculty, location, start and end dates, and section number. Students register for course offerings, not courses directly. Course offering schedule records capture day-by-day schedule variations, such as different meeting times and locations for different days of the week, allowing institutions to model complex scheduling patterns.\n- **Academic Terms** [Academic Operations]: Defines the academic calendar with terms, sessions, and time periods that structure when courses are offered and when milestones occur. Academic Years define the entirety of the academic year. Academic Terms specify academic periods which can hold other time periods within them. Academic Sessions specify the course offering time periods based on your institution's calendar, whether that is semesters, quarters, trimesters, or other configurations. These objects are flexible enough to accommodate different schedules, overlapping terms, and nontraditional intake cycles.\n- **Learning Objectives** [Academic Operations]: Captures measurable learning outcomes tied to courses and programs. Learning Outcome Items represent the mapping between a learning and its related outcome, enabling institutions to track whether students are achieving the intended results of their courses and programs. Learning Foundation Items define prerequisites, co-requisites, or recommended learning that is required before a student can enroll or receive credit for a given learning outcome.\n- **Transfer Credits & Equivalencies** [Academic Operations]: Evaluates and maps credits earned at other institutions to equivalent courses in the catalog. An applicant creates a course credit transfer application for requests and decisions at a course, degree, or experience level. The application includes potential transfer courses, approved learning equivalencies, and verified external learning participant results from a transcript. The registrar manages the application, and a case is opened to initiate the administrative process at a college, experience, or transcript level.\n- **Program Enrollment** [Enrollment]: Records a student's admission and active participation in a degree program or certificate. The Learner Program object tracks a student's enrollment in a learning program, including their academic standing and progress toward completion. When combined with Academic Term Enrollment records, the system maintains a term-by-term view of each student's participation. Academic Term Enrollment records must be active and contain an enrollment date for the Student Management app to display enrollment information correctly.\n- **Course Registration** [Enrollment]: Manages a student's registration in specific course offerings for a given term. Course Offering Participant records link students to the courses they are taking, capturing the registration status, credit mode, and role. Course Offering Participant Result records track the outcomes of each registration, including grades and completion status. These records accumulate to build the student's academic transcript and feed into GPA calculations.\n- **Academic Achievement** [Enrollment]: Records grades, credits earned, and academic milestones that mark a student's progress toward degree completion. Learning Achievement Configuration maps learning achievement types to record types, enabling institutions to categorize outcomes by their nature. Standard configurations include Learning Course, Learning Program, and Achievement Group, with optional configurations for Skill, Degree, and Diploma. Every learning achievement type requires at least one configuration record, and the standard configuration records cannot be deleted.\n- **Enrollment Status Management** [Enrollment]: Tracks and enforces enrollment lifecycle states including active, hold, probation, suspension, leave of absence, and withdrawal. Service Process Studio lets institutions design seamless customer service processes that staff can launch to handle common registrar operations. Use cases include handling requests for course substitutions, course waivers, term withdrawals, transcripts, and degree and graduation certificates. Student operations include changing contact information, changing learning programs, and new or changed declarations of majors and minors.\n- **Learning Plans** [Enrollment]: Creates personalized academic roadmaps that sequence courses across terms toward degree completion. Learning Pathway Templates provide a reusable template that a learner can apply to create a planned learning path. Each template contains Learning Pathway Template Items representing requirements with completion details, and Learning Pathway Template Program Plans that connect specific program plans to the template. This allows institutions to create standard degree pathways that students can adopt and customize.\n- **Person Accounts** [Student Records]: The core student record built on the Salesforce Person Account model, combining Account and Contact functionality into a single entity. Faculty, staff, administrators, students, and alumni are modeled with the Person Account object, which is a standard Salesforce object. The Contact Profile object is associated with the Contact object and allows tracking of biographic and demographic information. When this data is woven together, the result is a unified student record that helps institutions see, understand, and serve the whole person behind the data.\n- **Contact Points** [Student Records]: Manages multiple addresses, phone numbers, and email addresses for each student with usage designations like home, school, billing, and emergency. Contact Point Address, Contact Point Phone, and Contact Point Email objects are added to the Person Account page layout through the Student Management app setup. Each student can have multiple addresses, phone numbers, and email addresses with different usage types such as home, school, billing, and permanent. Primary designation determines which contact point is used for official communications.\n- **Relationships & Household** [Student Records]: Maps family, guardian, and household relationships between person records using Group Membership objects, Account Contact Relationships, and Contact Contact Relationships. Education Cloud uses a variety of objects to represent people, families, organizations, and relationships. Person accounts represent nearly all individuals, while household accounts represent families and business accounts represent organizations, schools, colleges, departments, and services. Group Membership objects link individuals to households, other individuals, services, or organizations.\n- **Education History** [Student Records]: Stores prior education records from high school and previous institutions including school name, dates attended, degree earned, GPA, and class rank. Person Education records capture information about professional education for a person, including the institution name, dates attended, degree earned, GPA, and class rank. These records are created automatically when applicants enter their educational background through the application form, and they appear on both the student's records and the alumni profile page.\n- **Examinations & Test Scores** [Student Records]: Records standardized test scores including SAT, ACT, GRE, TOEFL, IELTS, and AP exams. Person Examination records store test names, dates taken, individual section scores, and composite or total scores. These records are created automatically when applicants enter their test information through the application form and are used during admissions evaluation, placement decisions, and credit-by-examination processing.\n- **Demographics & Languages** [Student Records]: Captures language proficiency levels, employment history, and additional demographic information used for institutional reporting, compliance, and personalized student services. Person Language records store language proficiency information that supports international student services, ESL placement, and institutional compliance reporting. Person Employment records track work-study positions, internships, and post-graduation jobs, with employer name, job title, dates, and employment type. Post-graduation employment data feeds institutional career outcome reporting.\n- **Competency Tracking** [Student Success]: Records and assesses student skills and proficiencies against defined competency frameworks. Person Competency records document a student's skills and proficiencies, such as Python programming or public speaking, with assessed proficiency levels. These records are accessed by the Student Goals Agent's grounding flow to provide context-aware recommendations. Competencies can be mapped to learning objectives, enabling outcome-based education tracking where students demonstrate mastery.\n- **Traits & Affinities** [Student Success]: Captures student strengths, personality characteristics, and interest areas that inform personalized advising and career guidance. Person Traits capture unique student characteristics or attributes, such as Leader or Detail-Oriented, identified through assessments or advisor observations. Person Affinities map the student's preferences and interests, such as specific academic subjects, career aspirations, or extracurricular activities. Both are used by the Student Goals Agent's grounding flow to provide context-aware recommendations.\n- **Academic Advising** [Student Success]: Coordinates advisor-to-student assignments and tracks advising interactions, notes, and action items. The Student Success app enables advisors to create and manage personalized care plans that help learners achieve educational success. Care plans include benefits, goals, and tasks assigned to students. Action plans provide task-managed checklists for to-do lists during enrollment, care plans for students, and application or matriculation processes. The Action Center component on the Experience site helps learners keep track of their care plans, action plans, and tasks.\n- **Academic Alerts** [Student Success]: Triggers early warning notifications when students show signs of academic difficulty, disengagement, or risk of dropout. Record Alerts enable advisors and staff to be notified about changes in records that require action, so staff can take proactive steps and leverage care plans for a learner. Alert schedules can be customized, and alerts can be automated using flows for mass application. OmniStudio allows customization of record alert cards to display the most relevant information for each alert type.\n- **Career Development** [Student Success]: Helps students explore career paths, set professional goals, and build career readiness through structured development activities. Career Planning and Life Goals enables students to access a library of career and interest assessments, explore campus involvement groups, track memberships and associated roles, and manage their profile and preferences more efficiently. Students can set, update, and track specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound career and life goals through the learner portal.\n- **Fee Management** [Student Financials]: Defines the institution's fee structure using Salesforce Products. Student Financials bridges the gap between students and their financial accounts by setting up a fee management framework in Education Cloud. The framework uses the Salesforce pricing and order engine adapted for higher education, loading tuition and fees for each academic interval and applying fees to learning programs and courses.\n- **Price Books & Schedules** [Student Financials]: Establishes term-specific pricing through Salesforce Price Books. Price books are associated with academic intervals through the Price Book Academic Interval object. Each interval, whether it is a session, term, or year, can have multiple price books to support different fee structures for different student populations such as in-state versus out-of-state, undergraduate versus graduate, or full-time versus part-time students.\n- **Academic Orders** [Student Financials]: Generates student financial charges by creating orders populated with fee products. Academic orders are generated using the Salesforce-provided Create Learner Order invocable action, which creates both an order for the learner and an associated academic order for the relevant academic term. The action can be incorporated into organizational workflows using flows, business APIs, and OmniStudio Flexcards. For bulk calculations across many students, institutions should use flows with batch management.\n- **Payment Processing** [Student Financials]: Tracks payments received, payment plans, and outstanding balances on student accounts. Student financial account management is enabled through the Education Cloud setup, which configures order creation settings and pricing settings including price book options. Sharing settings for financial objects including Academic Term, Academic Term Enrollment, Order, Order Product, Academic Order, Contact Profile, and Account must be set to Public Read Only for the system to function properly.\n- **Financial Aid** [Student Financials]: Manages scholarship, grant, and aid award packaging for eligible students. Financial aid awards interact with the pricing engine to calculate net cost to the student after aid is applied. The expression set template for student fee calculations can be customized to apply institutional scholarships, grants, and other discount types as part of the order generation process. This ensures that financial aid is reflected accurately on student account statements.\n- **Program Design** [Mentoring]: Defines mentoring programs with goals, eligibility criteria, duration, and available benefits. A mentoring program plays a pivotal role in enhancing the overall experience and personal development of members of your institution. Programs benefit participants through academic guidance, career development, personal growth and support, networking opportunities, retention and engagement, skill development, and diversity and inclusion. The mentorship experience can have a profound and lasting effect on participants.\n- **Mentor & Mentee Profiles** [Mentoring]: Captures detailed profiles for both mentors and mentees including skills, experience areas, availability, communication preferences, and goals. Mentoring profiles identify the role, preferences, and interests of participants. Profile fields are configurable per program, and possible comparison fields include subject area, industry, channel preference (virtual or in-person), days available, times available, skills, and location. Lookup relationships, master-detail relationships, and system fields are not supported for comparison.\n- **AI-Powered Matching** [Mentoring]: Uses Einstein comparison algorithms to analyze mentor and mentee profiles and recommend optimal pairings. Mentoring profile records help connect mentees with suitable mentors. Profile fields for comparison can include subject area or industry, in-person or virtual meeting preference, location, and days and times the participant is available. You can add any custom fields that help match the ideal mentor with each mentee, although lookup relationships, master-detail relationships, and system fields are not supported for comparison.\n- **Benefit Assignment & Tracking** [Mentoring]: Assigns and tracks the specific benefits a mentee receives from their mentoring relationship. The benefit assignment record page serves as the central management point for each mentoring relationship. Facilitators can see names and contact information for the enrollee (mentee) and benefit provider (mentor), take action such as creating alerts, adding notes, creating tasks, and sending email, and view a timeline of mentoring activities. Benefit assignment records should be created using the Benefit Assignments tab rather than the related list on the account record.\n- **Alumni Engagement** [Alumni & Advancement]: Tracks ongoing relationships with graduates through event participation, communication interactions, volunteer activities, and career updates. Education Cloud provides a 360-degree view of learners throughout their educational journey from prospect to proud, involved alumni. The Alumni Relations app enables staff to manage alumni information and help alumni stay engaged and invested in their alma mater. Alumni relations coordinators and managers get a single home page view of alumni activity with the ability to create action-based alerts and activities.\n- **Gift Management** [Alumni & Advancement]: Records and processes charitable gifts including cash, securities, in-kind donations, and matching gifts. When Fundraising is enabled in Education Cloud, institutions have access to all the features, objects, fields, invocable actions, and APIs needed to manage gifts. This includes gift transactions for tracking individual donations, gift designations for allocating funds to specific purposes, gift soft credits for recognition, and gift tributes for memorial or honorary gifts.\n- **Pledges & Commitments** [Alumni & Advancement]: Manages multi-year pledges and recurring giving commitments where donors commit to future gifts over a defined period. Gift commitments track the total pledged amount, payment schedule, amount received to date, and outstanding balance. Automated tasks simplify handling recurring donations, and institutions can easily monitor upcoming, missed, failed, and recently paid and refunded transactions. Commitment records link to individual gift transactions that fulfill the pledge over time.\n- **Volunteer Management** [Alumni & Advancement]: Coordinates alumni volunteer activities including mentoring current students, serving on advisory boards, participating in career panels, and supporting campus events. Volunteer Management enables institutions to manage volunteer programs such as alumni mentoring, parent associations, and campus events. In Experience Cloud, institutions create a portal to post opportunities and let volunteers browse, search, and sign up. The system collects and evaluates volunteer applications, schedules volunteers, tracks hours, and reports on volunteer impact.\n- **Fundraising Campaigns** [Alumni & Advancement]: Plans and executes fundraising campaigns with goals, timelines, prospect assignments, and progress tracking. Scoring frameworks help increase fundraising success by identifying donors who are the best fit for each campaign or outreach program. Matching donors to specific outreach endeavors improves fundraising outcomes and strengthens constituent relationships. The Recency, Frequency, and Monetary value (RFM) score is a standard framework available for donor analysis.\n- **Appointment Scheduling** [Appointments]: Enables students to book appointments with staff members based on department, service type, and available time slots. Education Cloud provides a central self-service system for managing appointments. Learners have visibility over staff availability in any department based on configured location and appointment channels. They can view and schedule appointments, and if the virtual appointments feature is set up, they can join virtually. Staff can also schedule appointments on behalf of learners from their records.\n- **Staff Availability** [Appointments]: Manages staff calendars, service territories, and availability windows for appointment scheduling. Service resources represent staff members who are available for student appointments. Each resource has defined working hours, skills, and service territory assignments that determine which appointment types they can fulfill and when they are available. Capacity settings control concurrent appointment limits, and blocked time prevents scheduling during meetings or preparation periods.\n- **Waitlist & Walk-ins** [Appointments]: Supports walk-in appointment flows with waitlist management and estimated wait times. Walk-in appointment management complements the scheduled appointment system by accommodating students who need immediate assistance. The waitlist feature integrates with the same service territory and service resource configuration used for scheduled appointments, ensuring consistent capacity management across both channels.\n- **Virtual Appointments** [Appointments]: Extends appointment scheduling with video conferencing integration for remote advising, tutoring, and counseling sessions. Virtual appointments are enabled by turning on the Video Calls feature in Education Cloud setup. Once enabled, virtual appointments automatically generate meeting links and embed them in confirmation notifications. This extends the standard Salesforce Scheduler appointment experience with remote meeting capabilities.\n- **Director Insights** [Education Analytics]: A multi-page dashboard providing institutional leadership with a comprehensive view of key performance indicators across recruitment, enrollment, retention, and graduation outcomes. Education Analytics works seamlessly with existing Education Cloud features, enabling institutions to improve processes and learner metrics. The dashboards and institutional key performance indicators provide insights into recruitment, admissions, learner engagement, and student success. The system uses CRM Analytics with custom education-specific recipes and data connections.\n- **Recruitment Analytics** [Education Analytics]: Tracks recruitment funnel metrics including inquiry volume, event attendance, application submission rates, and yield percentages by channel, territory, and counselor. The Recruitment and Admissions Insights dashboard is embedded in the Admissions Console home page, providing admissions officers with at-a-glance visibility into the health of the admissions pipeline. Directors can track progress toward goals with a variety of KPI reports from their own console, which includes recruitment analytics, actionable lists, and staff assignment tools.\n- **Student Success Metrics** [Education Analytics]: Monitors retention, persistence, GPA distribution, credit accumulation, and graduation rates across student populations. The Advisor Console in the Student Success app provides advisors with the ability to create and assign care plans, create alerts, view analytics dashboards for student success, view advisor insights and KPIs, and more. This home page is available out-of-the-box with Education Cloud and requires no additional setup to get started with student success monitoring.\n- **Financial Analytics** [Education Analytics]: Provides visibility into tuition revenue, financial aid distribution, receivables aging, and payment plan utilization. Education Analytics dashboards aggregate financial data including tuition revenue, financial aid distribution, and enrollment-driven revenue projections. The analytics app includes recipes that process data from across Education Cloud domains to produce financial KPIs visible to directors and administrators. Revenue forecasting models use admissions pipeline data to project future enrollment-driven revenue.\n- **Recruitment Agent** [Agentforce]: Automates personalized outreach to prospective students through email, SMS, and chat channels. The Student Recruitment Agent includes four topics: Admissions and Enrollments FAQ uses knowledge articles to answer questions, Admissions Application creates applications for students, Campus Tours Visits and Events Registration assists with event sign-ups, and Request for Information creates academic interest records when prospects request recruiter contact. The agent can be deployed for both authenticated and unauthenticated users.\n- **Admissions Agent** [Agentforce]: Provides real-time application status updates and answers common admissions questions through conversational AI. The Admissions and Enrollments FAQ topic uses the Answer Questions with Knowledge action to find information in institutional knowledge articles. The agent can also retrieve learning program data to provide context-aware responses about specific programs. For questions that cannot be answered by the agent, an escalation topic redirects unanswered conversations to human representatives.\n- **Student Success Agent** [Agentforce]: Assists students with academic planning, course selection, and career exploration through personalized conversations. Student Advising Topics in Agentforce includes the Student Advising and Campus Engagement topic with three standard actions: Summarize Advising Case for quickly understanding a learner's case, Find Advising Cases for locating relevant cases, and Find Campus Resources for answering questions about facilities, services, activities, clubs, programs, and action plans. The agent uses knowledge articles for policy guidance and Einstein search retrievers for campus resource discovery.\n- **Student Financials Agent** [Agentforce]: Answers questions about account balances, fee breakdowns, payment due dates, and financial aid status. The Student Financials Agent includes two topics: Student Fee Management provides detailed fee breakdowns and fee explanations for specific academic terms using Query Records, Get Record Details, Get Fee Details, and Get Fee Breakdown actions. The topic answers questions about fee amounts, fee descriptions, and optional fee types, using context from previous results to streamline explanations.\n- **Alumni Agent** [Agentforce]: Engages alumni through personalized communication about giving opportunities, events, and volunteer activities. Alumni Engagement Metrics uses sample prompts for the Engagement Visualization prompt template type to generate narrative summaries of alumni engagement. Four summarization categories are available: Overall Alumni Engagements for a high-level activity summary, Events and Activities for experiential engagement, Personal Engagement for meaningful communications, and Meaningful Impact for volunteerism contributions.\n- **Student Portal** [Experience Cloud]: A self-service hub where enrolled students access their academic records, register for courses, view grades, and manage their personal information. The Education Portal template in Experience Builder provides education-specific components for building a learner-facing self-service site. Students can view their success team and assigned advisors, view advisor details and post questions, schedule and manage appointments, enroll into support programs and take assessments, view care plans, goals, and benefits, and manage tasks and action plans.\n- **Applicant Portal** [Experience Cloud]: Provides prospective and active applicants with a dedicated workspace for managing their application. The Education Portal template provides a starting point for building an applicant-facing self-service site. The portal collects information from prospective students and records it in Salesforce. Audiences in Experience Builder create separate views for different user types, enabling applicants to see their own application data, document checklists, and decision notifications while restricting access to other students' information.\n- **Alumni Portal** [Experience Cloud]: An online community for graduates to stay connected with their institution, update career information, explore giving opportunities, and register for alumni events. Education Cloud provides Lightning components for creating an alumni community where graduates can connect with each other. The Alumni Profile component allows users to share information about their education and professional experience, with data sourced from the Person Education and Person Employment objects. The Person Public Profile component powers the alumni directory where users can search for and connect with one another.\n- **Mobile Experience** [Experience Cloud]: Responsive design ensures all portal functionality works seamlessly across smartphones and tablets. The Education Portal template in Experience Builder creates responsive sites that automatically adapt to different screen sizes. Mobile-optimized navigation and touch-friendly form inputs provide a native-like experience through the mobile browser. Students can access their personalized dashboard, view alerts, check appointment schedules, and interact with AI agents from their mobile devices.\n- **Data Consolidation** [Data 360]: Ingests student data from legacy student information systems, admissions platforms, and external databases into Education Cloud. Educational data comes from multiple institutional systems: student information systems containing profile information, course registrations, fee payments, attendance records, and grades; learning management systems with login credentials, usage patterns, interactions, and assessments; and enterprise resource planning systems with financial records, tuition, financial aid, billing, and financial holds. Institutions also use data on housing, dining, event registration, and many other campus services.\n- **Identity Resolution** [Data 360]: Detects and resolves duplicate student records across source systems using configurable matching rules. The Education data kit includes an Alumni Identity Resolution Ruleset that defines matching rules for linking multiple sources of data into a unified profile. Match rules evaluate combinations of identifying fields such as name, date of birth, email, and student ID using exact, fuzzy, or phonetic comparison methods, each with a configurable importance weight that determines its contribution to the overall confidence score.\n- **Unified Records** [Data 360]: Creates a single, authoritative record for each individual by merging the best data from multiple sources. The Education data kit provides calculated insights out-of-the-box to help understand learner behavior. The Alumni Engagement bundle includes Comprehensive Engagements, Comprehensive with Unified Individual, Philanthropic Status, and Status of Giving insights. The Student Success bundle includes a Student Course Percentage Calculator. These insights can be activated and scheduled to publish on a regular cadence.\n- **Data Mapping & Standards** [Data 360]: Establishes field-level mappings between external source system schemas and the Education Cloud data model. After connecting a data source, Data 360 accesses it so that you can create mapping sets between the objects and fields within the source and the Education Cloud data model objects. The Education data kit provides prebuilt mappings to key data model objects in six bundles covering Education Cloud, Academic Operations, Alumni Engagement, Fundraising, Recruiting and Admissions, and Student Success.\n\n## Key Objects (54)\n### Recruitment\n- **Lead**: Represents a prospective student who has expressed interest in the institution but has not yet applied.\n- **ContactProfile**: Stores additional demographic and biographical information about a prospect or student beyond the core person account.\n- **Campaign**: Represents a recruitment campaign, event, or outreach initiative used to attract prospective students.\n- **CampaignMember**: Links a prospect or student to a specific campaign, tracking their participation and response status.\n### Admissions\n- **IndividualApplication**: The primary application record that tracks a prospective student's application to a specific program and term.\n- **Applicant**: Links an individual application to the person account that represents the applying student.\n- **DocumentChecklistItem**: Tracks a required or optional document within an application's submission checklist.\n- **PreliminaryApplication**: A lightweight application form that captures early interest from prospective students before the formal application window opens.\n### Academic Operations\n- **Program**: Defines a degree program, certificate, or academic pathway offered by the institution.\n- **Course**: A permanent course definition in the institutional catalog, separate from its scheduled instances.\n- **CourseOffering**: A specific instance of a course scheduled for a particular academic term with assigned instructors, meeting times, and enrollment capacity.\n- **AcademicTerm**: Defines a period in the academic calendar during which courses are offered and academic activities occur.\n- **AcademicTimePeriod**: A subdivision of an academic term for institutions that run multiple sessions within a single term.\n- **LearningObjective**: A measurable learning outcome that describes what a student should know or be able to do upon completing a course or program.\n- **TransferCredit**: Records credits earned at an external institution that have been evaluated and accepted for transfer.\n- **LearningEquivalency**: Defines how courses from external institutions map to equivalent courses in the institutional catalog.\n### Enrollment\n- **ProgramEnrollment**: Records a student's active participation in a degree program or certificate.\n- **CourseOfferingParticipant**: Tracks a student's registration in a specific course offering for a given term.\n- **LearningAchievement**: Records a student's grade, credits earned, and academic milestone for a specific course offering.\n- **LearningPlan**: A personalized academic roadmap that sequences courses across terms toward degree completion.\n### Student Records\n- **Account**: The core person account record that serves as the unified student identity across all Education Cloud domains.\n- **ContactPointAddress**: Stores a physical or mailing address associated with a person account.\n- **ContactPointPhone**: Stores a phone number associated with a person account with usage type designation.\n- **ContactPointEmail**: Stores an email address associated with a person account with usage type and primary designation.\n- **ContactRelationship**: Defines a relationship between two person accounts such as parent-child, guardian, sibling, or spouse.\n- **PersonEducation**: Records a student's prior education at another institution, capturing the school name, dates attended, degree earned, GPA, and class rank.\n- **PersonExamination**: Records standardized test results including SAT, ACT, GRE, TOEFL, IELTS, and AP examinations.\n- **PersonLanguage**: Records language proficiency information for a student including reading, writing, speaking, and listening skill levels.\n- **PersonEmployment**: Tracks a student's employment history including work-study positions, internships, and post-graduation jobs.\n### Student Success\n- **PersonCompetency**: Records a student's proficiency in a specific skill or competency area.\n- **PersonTrait**: Captures observable behavioral strengths and characteristics identified through assessments or advisor observations.\n- **PersonAffinity**: Records a student's academic subject interests, career aspirations, and extracurricular preferences.\n- **CareCoordinator**: Assigns an advisor or support staff member to a student for academic guidance, mentoring coordination, or crisis support.\n- **CareRole**: Defines the types of support roles available for care coordinator assignments.\n- **Case**: Used as an academic alert or support case when a student shows signs of difficulty.\n### Student Financials\n- **Product2**: Represents a fee type in the institution's financial structure such as tuition per credit hour, technology fees, lab fees, or meal plans.\n- **Pricebook2**: A collection of fee amounts effective for a specific academic term or student population.\n- **PricebookEntry**: Links a fee product to a specific price book with the monetary amount for that combination.\n- **AcademicOrder**: A student financial order that aggregates all charges for a specific term into a single record.\n- **OrderProduct**: An individual line item on an academic order representing a specific fee charge.\n### Mentoring\n- **MentoringProgram**: Defines a structured mentoring initiative with goals, eligibility criteria, duration, and available benefits.\n- **MentoringProfile**: Captures detailed information about a mentor or mentee for profile-based matching.\n- **MentoringBenefit**: Defines a type of support available within a mentoring program such as tutoring, career advice, networking introductions, or skill workshops.\n- **MentoringBenefitAssignment**: Records the assignment of a specific mentoring benefit to a mentee by their mentor.\n### Alumni & Advancement\n- **GiftTransaction**: Records a charitable donation made by an alumni or supporter.\n- **GiftCommitment**: Represents a donor's multi-year pledge or recurring giving commitment.\n- **VolunteerActivity**: Records an alumni volunteer's participation in an institutional activity such as mentoring, advisory board service, career panels, or campus events.\n### Appointments\n- **ServiceAppointment**: Represents a scheduled or walk-in appointment between a student and a staff member.\n- **ServiceResource**: Represents a staff member who is available for student appointments.\n- **ServiceTerritory**: Defines a department, office, or location where appointments are offered.\n### Data 360\n- **DataStream**: Defines a data ingestion connection from a legacy source system into Education Cloud.\n- **IdentityResolutionRuleset**: A collection of matching rules used to detect and resolve duplicate student records across source systems.\n- **MatchRule**: An individual matching criterion within an identity resolution ruleset.\n- **UnifiedIndividual**: The result of identity resolution, representing a single authoritative record for an individual created by merging data from multiple source systems.\n\n## Custom Metadata Types (6)\n### Recruitment\n- **RecruitmentSetting__mdt** (Recruitment Settings): Configures recruitment behavior including lead scoring activation, default lead sources for web inquiries, and automatic territory assignment rules for new prospects.\n### Admissions\n- **AdmissionsSetting__mdt** (Admissions Settings): Configures admissions processing behavior including review workflow activation, automatic decision score thresholds, and document verification requirements.\n### Student Success\n- **AlertThreshold__mdt** (Alert Thresholds): Configures the thresholds at which academic alerts are triggered, such as minimum GPA levels, attendance rates, and assignment completion percentages that generate early warning cases.\n### Student Financials\n- **FinancialAidRule__mdt** (Financial Aid Rules): Configures financial aid packaging rules including eligibility criteria, maximum award amounts, and whether multiple aid types can be combined for the same student.\n- **FeeCalculationRule__mdt** (Fee Calculation Rules): Defines rules for calculating student fees based on attributes like residency status, enrollment intensity, and program level.\n### Mentoring\n- **MentoringMatchCriteria__mdt** (Mentoring Match Criteria): Configures which profile fields are used for AI-powered mentor-mentee matching and their relative importance weights.\n\n## Object Fields\n### Lead (6 fields)\n- FirstName (Text): Prospect's first name\n- LastName (Text): Prospect's last name\n- Email (Email): Primary email address for recruitment communications\n- LeadSource (Picklist): Channel through which the prospect first engaged (web inquiry, campus event, referral)\n- Status (Picklist): Current stage in the recruitment funnel (new, contacted, qualified, converted)\n- Company (Text): High school or current institution name\n### ContactProfile (4 fields)\n- CitizenshipStatus (Picklist): Citizenship classification (citizen, permanent resident, international)\n- ResidencyStatus (Picklist): In-state or out-of-state residency for tuition classification\n- PreferredName (Text): Name the student prefers to be called\n- ContactId (Lookup): Reference to the person account contact record\n### Campaign (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Campaign name\n- Type (Picklist): Campaign type (event, email, social media, direct mail)\n- Status (Picklist): Campaign lifecycle status (planned, active, completed)\n- StartDate (Date): Campaign start date\n- EndDate (Date): Campaign end date\n- NumberOfLeads (Number): Total leads generated by this campaign\n### CampaignMember (4 fields)\n- Status (Picklist): Response status within the campaign (sent, responded, attended, converted)\n- CampaignId (Lookup): Reference to the parent campaign\n- LeadId (Lookup): Reference to the lead record if the member is a prospect\n- ContactId (Lookup): Reference to the contact record if the member is an existing student\n### IndividualApplication (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated application identifier\n- ApplicationStatus (Picklist): Current status (draft, submitted, under review, decision rendered)\n- ApplicationType (Picklist): Type of application (freshman, transfer, graduate, international)\n- SubmittedDate (DateTime): Timestamp when the applicant submitted the application\n- DecisionStatus (Picklist): Admission decision (accepted, denied, waitlisted, conditional)\n- ProgramId (Lookup): The academic program the applicant is applying to\n### Applicant (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Applicant display name\n- AccountId (Lookup): Reference to the person account\n- IndividualApplicationId (Lookup): Reference to the application record\n- ApplicantType (Picklist): Applicant classification (first-time, transfer, returning)\n### DocumentChecklistItem (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Document type name (transcript, essay, recommendation letter)\n- Status (Picklist): Document status (required, received, verified, waived)\n- IsRequired (Checkbox): Whether this document is mandatory for application completion\n- ReceivedDate (Date): Date the document was received\n- ParentRecordId (Lookup): Reference to the parent application record\n### PreliminaryApplication (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Applicant name\n- IntendedProgram (Text): Program the prospect is interested in\n- IntendedTerm (Text): Academic term of intended enrollment\n- Status (Picklist): Preliminary application status\n- AccountId (Lookup): Reference to the person account\n### Program (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Program title (e.g., Bachelor of Science in Computer Science)\n- ProgramType (Picklist): Degree type (bachelor, master, doctoral, certificate)\n- TotalCreditsRequired (Number): Minimum credits needed for completion\n- MinimumGPA (Number): Minimum cumulative GPA required for good standing\n- DepartmentId (Lookup): Academic department that owns this program\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether the program is actively accepting enrollments\n### Course (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Course title\n- CourseCode (Text): Subject area and course number (e.g., CS 101)\n- CreditValue (Number): Number of credits awarded upon completion\n- Description (LongTextArea): Course description for the catalog\n- Level (Picklist): Course level (introductory, intermediate, advanced, graduate)\n### CourseOffering (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Offering display name including section number\n- SectionNumber (Text): Section identifier within the term\n- Capacity (Number): Maximum enrollment capacity\n- DeliveryMode (Picklist): Instruction mode (in-person, online, hybrid)\n- CourseId (Lookup): Reference to the parent course definition\n- AcademicTermId (Lookup): The academic term this offering is scheduled in\n### AcademicTerm (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Term name (e.g., Fall 2026, Spring 2027)\n- StartDate (Date): First day of the term\n- EndDate (Date): Last day of the term\n- RegistrationStartDate (Date): When course registration opens\n- RegistrationEndDate (Date): Registration deadline\n- Type (Picklist): Term type (fall, spring, summer, winter)\n### AcademicTimePeriod (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Time period name (e.g., Summer Session A)\n- StartDate (Date): Period start date\n- EndDate (Date): Period end date\n- AcademicTermId (Lookup): Parent academic term\n### LearningObjective (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Objective title\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed statement of what the student will achieve\n- AssessmentMethod (Picklist): How achievement is measured (exam, project, portfolio)\n- CourseId (Lookup): Course this objective belongs to\n### TransferCredit (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Transfer credit display name\n- OriginatingInstitution (Text): Name of the institution where credits were earned\n- OriginalCourseName (Text): Course title at the originating institution\n- CreditValue (Number): Number of credits transferred\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### LearningEquivalency (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Equivalency rule name\n- ExternalCourseName (Text): Course name at the external institution\n- ExternalInstitution (Text): Institution the equivalency applies to\n- InternalCourseId (Lookup): The equivalent internal course\n- CreditValue (Number): Credits awarded for the equivalency\n### ProgramEnrollment (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): System-generated enrollment identifier\n- EnrollmentStatus (Picklist): Current status (active, on hold, leave, withdrawn, graduated)\n- StartDate (Date): Enrollment start date\n- ExpectedGraduationDate (Date): Projected graduation date\n- CumulativeGPA (Number): Running cumulative grade point average\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n- ProgramId (Lookup): Academic program the student is enrolled in\n### CourseOfferingParticipant (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Participant display name\n- ParticipantRole (Picklist): Role in the offering (student, TA, auditor)\n- RegistrationStatus (Picklist): Status (registered, waitlisted, dropped, completed)\n- CreditMode (Picklist): Credit type (credit, audit, pass-fail)\n- CourseOfferingId (Lookup): The course offering this participant is registered in\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### LearningAchievement (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Achievement display name\n- GradeValue (Text): Letter grade or pass/fail designation\n- CreditsEarned (Number): Credits awarded for this achievement\n- CreditsAttempted (Number): Credits attempted (may differ for withdrawals)\n- QualityPoints (Number): Grade points used in GPA calculation\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### LearningPlan (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Plan display name\n- Status (Picklist): Plan status (draft, active, completed)\n- TargetCompletionDate (Date): Projected completion date\n- TotalPlannedCredits (Number): Total credits mapped in the plan\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### Account (6 fields)\n- FirstName (Text): Student's first name\n- LastName (Text): Student's last name\n- PersonBirthdate (Date): Date of birth\n- StudentId__c (Text): Institutional student identifier\n- PersonEmail (Email): Primary email address\n- RecordTypeId (Lookup): Person account record type\n### ContactPointAddress (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Address label (home, school, billing)\n- Street (TextArea): Street address lines\n- City (Text): City name\n- StateCode (Text): State or province\n- PostalCode (Text): ZIP or postal code\n- Country (Text): Country name\n- UsageType (Picklist): Address purpose (home, school, billing, permanent)\n### ContactPointPhone (4 fields)\n- TelephoneNumber (Phone): Phone number\n- UsageType (Picklist): Phone usage type (mobile, home, work)\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the primary phone number\n- ParentId (Lookup): Reference to the person account\n### ContactPointEmail (4 fields)\n- EmailAddress (Email): Email address\n- UsageType (Picklist): Email usage type (personal, institutional, work)\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the primary email\n- ParentId (Lookup): Reference to the person account\n### ContactRelationship (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Relationship display name\n- Type (Picklist): Relationship type (parent, guardian, sibling, spouse, emergency)\n- IsPrimaryContact (Checkbox): Whether this is the primary family contact\n- ContactId (Lookup): The student in the relationship\n- RelatedContactId (Lookup): The related person\n### PersonEducation (6 fields)\n- InstitutionName (Text): Name of the school or institution\n- DegreeEarned (Text): Degree or diploma earned\n- GPA (Number): Grade point average at the institution\n- StartDate (Date): Attendance start date\n- EndDate (Date): Attendance end date\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonExamination (5 fields)\n- ExamName (Text): Name of the examination (SAT, ACT, GRE)\n- ExamDate (Date): Date the exam was taken\n- TotalScore (Number): Composite or total score\n- SectionScores (LongTextArea): Individual section scores\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonLanguage (4 fields)\n- Language (Picklist): Language name\n- ProficiencyLevel (Picklist): Overall proficiency (beginner, intermediate, advanced, native)\n- IsPrimary (Checkbox): Whether this is the student's primary language\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonEmployment (6 fields)\n- EmployerName (Text): Name of the employer\n- JobTitle (Text): Position title\n- StartDate (Date): Employment start date\n- EndDate (Date): Employment end date (null if current)\n- EmploymentType (Picklist): Type (full-time, part-time, internship, work-study)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonCompetency (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Competency name\n- ProficiencyLevel (Picklist): Current proficiency (developing, proficient, advanced, expert)\n- AssessmentDate (Date): Date the competency was last assessed\n- AssessmentMethod (Picklist): How proficiency was measured (exam, project, observation)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonTrait (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Trait name\n- Category (Picklist): Trait category (academic, interpersonal, leadership)\n- Strength (Picklist): Strength level (emerging, developing, strong)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### PersonAffinity (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Affinity name\n- Type (Picklist): Affinity type (academic interest, career aspiration, extracurricular)\n- InterestLevel (Picklist): Degree of interest (casual, moderate, strong)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### CareCoordinator (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Coordinator assignment name\n- Role (Picklist): Support role (academic advisor, career counselor, student affairs)\n- StartDate (Date): Assignment start date\n- EndDate (Date): Assignment end date (null if current)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student being supported\n- CoordinatorId (Lookup): Staff member providing support\n### CareRole (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Role title\n- Description (TextArea): Role scope and responsibilities\n- MaxCaseload (Number): Maximum number of students per coordinator\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this role is currently available for assignment\n### Case (6 fields)\n- Subject (Text): Alert or case subject\n- Status (Picklist): Case status (new, in progress, resolved, closed)\n- Priority (Picklist): Urgency level (low, medium, high, critical)\n- Type (Picklist): Case type (academic alert, conduct, financial hold, general)\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n- Description (LongTextArea): Detailed description of the alert or issue\n### Product2 (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Fee product name (e.g., In-State Tuition Per Credit)\n- ProductCode (Text): Unique fee code\n- Family (Picklist): Fee family (tuition, fees, housing, meal plans)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this fee is currently applicable\n- Description (TextArea): Fee description\n### Pricebook2 (3 fields)\n- Name (Text): Price book name (e.g., Fall 2026 Undergraduate)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this price book is active\n- Description (TextArea): Price book description and applicability\n### PricebookEntry (4 fields)\n- UnitPrice (Currency): Fee amount\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this entry is active\n- Product2Id (Lookup): Reference to the fee product\n- Pricebook2Id (Lookup): Reference to the price book\n### AcademicOrder (6 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): Order identifier\n- Status (Picklist): Order status (draft, activated, paid, past due)\n- TotalAmount (Currency): Total charges on the order\n- TermId (Lookup): Academic term this order covers\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n- EffectiveDate (Date): Date the order becomes effective\n### OrderProduct (5 fields)\n- Quantity (Number): Number of units (e.g., credit hours)\n- UnitPrice (Currency): Price per unit\n- TotalPrice (Currency): Line item total (quantity x unit price)\n- OrderId (Lookup): Parent academic order\n- Product2Id (Lookup): Fee product being charged\n### MentoringProgram (6 fields)\n- Name (Text): Program name\n- ProgramType (Picklist): Type of mentoring (peer, career, academic, alumni)\n- Status (Picklist): Program status (planned, active, completed)\n- StartDate (Date): Program start date\n- EndDate (Date): Program end date\n- MaxParticipants (Number): Maximum mentee capacity\n### MentoringProfile (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Profile display name\n- Role (Picklist): Participant role (mentor, mentee)\n- Skills (LongTextArea): Skills and areas of expertise\n- Goals (LongTextArea): Mentoring goals and expectations\n- Availability (Picklist): Availability level (weekly, biweekly, monthly)\n- ProgramId (Lookup): Mentoring program this profile belongs to\n- AccountId (Lookup): Person account of the participant\n### MentoringBenefit (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Benefit name\n- Type (Picklist): Benefit type (tutoring, coaching, networking, workshop)\n- Description (TextArea): What this benefit provides\n- Frequency (Picklist): Expected delivery frequency (weekly, monthly, as needed)\n- ProgramId (Lookup): Program this benefit belongs to\n### MentoringBenefitAssignment (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Assignment display name\n- Status (Picklist): Assignment status (assigned, in progress, completed)\n- AssignedDate (Date): Date the benefit was assigned\n- CompletedDate (Date): Date the benefit was delivered\n- BenefitId (Lookup): Reference to the mentoring benefit\n- MentorProfileId (Lookup): Reference to the mentor's profile\n- MenteeProfileId (Lookup): Reference to the mentee's profile\n### GiftTransaction (7 fields)\n- Name (AutoNumber): Transaction identifier\n- Amount (Currency): Gift amount\n- GiftDate (Date): Date the gift was made\n- Designation (Picklist): Fund designation (unrestricted, scholarship, building, endowment)\n- PaymentMethod (Picklist): How the gift was made (check, credit card, wire, securities)\n- AcknowledgmentStatus (Picklist): Status of the tax acknowledgment letter\n- DonorId (Lookup): Person account of the donor\n### GiftCommitment (7 fields)\n- Name (Text): Commitment display name\n- TotalAmount (Currency): Total pledged amount\n- AmountReceived (Currency): Amount paid to date\n- PaymentSchedule (Picklist): Payment frequency (monthly, quarterly, annually)\n- StartDate (Date): Pledge start date\n- EndDate (Date): Pledge end date\n- DonorId (Lookup): Person account of the pledging donor\n### VolunteerActivity (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Activity name\n- ActivityType (Picklist): Type of volunteer activity (mentoring, board service, event, career panel)\n- HoursContributed (Number): Hours spent on the activity\n- ActivityDate (Date): Date of the activity\n- VolunteerId (Lookup): Person account of the volunteer\n### ServiceAppointment (7 fields)\n- Subject (Text): Appointment subject or topic\n- Status (Picklist): Appointment status (scheduled, checked in, completed, no show)\n- SchedStartTime (DateTime): Scheduled start time\n- SchedEndTime (DateTime): Scheduled end time\n- AppointmentType (Picklist): Meeting type (advising, tutoring, financial aid, administrative)\n- ServiceTerritoryId (Lookup): Department or location for the appointment\n- AccountId (Lookup): Student person account\n### ServiceResource (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Staff member name\n- ResourceType (Picklist): Resource type (advisor, tutor, counselor, administrator)\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this resource is currently available\n- RelatedRecordId (Lookup): Reference to the staff user record\n### ServiceTerritory (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Territory name (e.g., Academic Advising Center)\n- Description (TextArea): Territory description and services offered\n- IsActive (Checkbox): Whether this territory is currently active\n- OperatingHoursId (Lookup): Operating hours configuration\n### DataStream (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Data stream name\n- SourceSystem (Text): Name of the external source system\n- Status (Picklist): Stream status (active, paused, error)\n- Schedule (Text): Extraction schedule (daily, hourly, real-time)\n- LastRunDate (DateTime): Timestamp of the last successful extraction\n### IdentityResolutionRuleset (4 fields)\n- Name (Text): Ruleset name\n- Status (Picklist): Ruleset status (active, draft, disabled)\n- AutoMergeThreshold (Percent): Confidence score above which records merge automatically\n- ReviewThreshold (Percent): Confidence score above which records are flagged for manual review\n### MatchRule (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Rule name\n- MatchField (Text): The field being compared (email, name, date of birth)\n- MatchType (Picklist): Comparison method (exact, fuzzy, phonetic)\n- Weight (Number): Importance weight for scoring (1-100)\n- RulesetId (Lookup): Parent identity resolution ruleset\n### UnifiedIndividual (5 fields)\n- Name (Text): Unified record display name\n- SourceCount (Number): Number of source records that were merged\n- ConfidenceScore (Percent): Overall confidence in the identity match\n- LastResolvedDate (DateTime): Timestamp of the last resolution run\n- AccountId (Lookup): Reference to the resulting person account\n\n## Object Relationships\n- Lead -> Campaign (lookup): Leads are associated with recruitment campaigns through campaign members\n- ContactProfile -> Account (child): Each contact profile belongs to a person account\n- Campaign -> CampaignMember (parent): Campaigns contain campaign member records for each participant\n- CampaignMember -> Campaign (child): Each member belongs to a campaign\n- CampaignMember -> Lead (lookup): Member may reference a lead record\n- IndividualApplication -> Applicant (parent): Each application has an applicant record linking to the person\n- IndividualApplication -> Program (lookup): Applications reference the target academic program\n- IndividualApplication -> DocumentChecklistItem (parent): Applications have required document checklist items\n- Applicant -> Account (lookup): Each applicant references a person account\n- Applicant -> IndividualApplication (child): Each applicant is linked to an application\n- DocumentChecklistItem -> IndividualApplication (child): Checklist items belong to an application\n- PreliminaryApplication -> Account (lookup): Preliminary applications link to person accounts\n- PreliminaryApplication -> Program (lookup): References the intended academic program\n- Program -> ProgramEnrollment (parent): Programs have enrolled students through program enrollment records\n- Program -> Course (parent): Programs define required and elective courses\n- Course -> CourseOffering (parent): Courses have multiple offerings across terms\n- Course -> Program (lookup): Courses belong to academic programs\n- CourseOffering -> Course (child): Each offering belongs to a course\n- CourseOffering -> AcademicTerm (lookup): Offerings are scheduled within academic terms\n- CourseOffering -> CourseOfferingParticipant (parent): Offerings have registered participants\n- AcademicTerm -> CourseOffering (parent): Terms contain course offerings\n- AcademicTerm -> AcademicTimePeriod (parent): Terms can be subdivided into time periods\n- AcademicTimePeriod -> AcademicTerm (child): Each time period belongs to an academic term\n- LearningObjective -> Course (child): Objectives are defined within courses\n- LearningObjective -> PersonCompetency (lookup): Objectives map to competency assessments\n- TransferCredit -> Account (child): Transfer credits belong to a student\n- TransferCredit -> LearningEquivalency (lookup): Transfer credits reference equivalency rules for mapping\n- LearningEquivalency -> Course (lookup): Equivalencies map to internal course definitions\n- ProgramEnrollment -> Account (child): Each enrollment belongs to a student\n- ProgramEnrollment -> Program (lookup): Enrollment references the academic program\n- CourseOfferingParticipant -> CourseOffering (child): Participants belong to a course offering\n- CourseOfferingParticipant -> Account (lookup): Participants reference the student person account\n- LearningAchievement -> Account (child): Achievements belong to a student\n- LearningAchievement -> CourseOffering (lookup): Achievements reference the completed course offering\n- LearningPlan -> Account (child): Learning plans belong to a student\n- LearningPlan -> ProgramEnrollment (lookup): Plans are tied to a specific program enrollment\n- Account -> ProgramEnrollment (parent): Students have program enrollments\n- Account -> ContactRelationship (parent): Students have relationship records to family members\n- Account -> PersonEducation (parent): Students have education history records\n- ContactPointAddress -> Account (child): Addresses belong to a person account\n- ContactPointPhone -> Account (child): Phone records belong to a person account\n- ContactPointEmail -> Account (child): Email records belong to a person account\n- ContactRelationship -> Account (child): Relationships link two person accounts\n- PersonEducation -> Account (child): Education history belongs to a student\n- PersonExamination -> Account (child): Examination records belong to a student\n- PersonLanguage -> Account (child): Language records belong to a student\n- PersonEmployment -> Account (child): Employment records belong to a student\n- PersonCompetency -> Account (child): Competencies belong to a student\n- PersonCompetency -> LearningObjective (lookup): Competencies map to learning objectives\n- PersonTrait -> Account (child): Traits belong to a student\n- PersonAffinity -> Account (child): Affinities belong to a student\n- CareCoordinator -> Account (child): Care coordinators are assigned to students\n- CareRole -> CareCoordinator (parent): Roles are assigned to care coordinator records\n- Case -> Account (child): Cases are filed for a student\n- Product2 -> PricebookEntry (parent): Products have price book entries for term-specific pricing\n- Pricebook2 -> PricebookEntry (parent): Price books contain price book entries\n- PricebookEntry -> Product2 (child): Entries belong to a product\n- PricebookEntry -> Pricebook2 (child): Entries belong to a price book\n- AcademicOrder -> Account (child): Orders belong to a student\n- AcademicOrder -> OrderProduct (parent): Orders contain line items\n- AcademicOrder -> AcademicTerm (lookup): Orders reference the academic term\n- OrderProduct -> AcademicOrder (child): Line items belong to an order\n- OrderProduct -> Product2 (lookup): Line items reference a fee product\n- MentoringProgram -> MentoringProfile (parent): Programs have mentor and mentee profiles\n- MentoringProgram -> MentoringBenefit (parent): Programs define available benefits\n- MentoringProfile -> MentoringProgram (child): Profiles belong to a mentoring program\n- MentoringProfile -> Account (lookup): Profiles reference a person account\n- MentoringBenefit -> MentoringProgram (child): Benefits belong to a mentoring program\n- MentoringBenefit -> MentoringBenefitAssignment (parent): Benefits are assigned through assignment records\n- MentoringBenefitAssignment -> MentoringBenefit (child): Assignments reference a benefit type\n- MentoringBenefitAssignment -> MentoringProfile (lookup): Assignments link mentor and mentee profiles\n- GiftTransaction -> Account (child): Gift transactions belong to a donor\n- GiftTransaction -> GiftCommitment (lookup): Transactions may fulfill a pledge commitment\n- GiftCommitment -> Account (child): Commitments belong to a donor\n- GiftCommitment -> GiftTransaction (parent): Commitments are fulfilled by gift transactions\n- VolunteerActivity -> Account (child): Volunteer activities belong to an alumni\n- ServiceAppointment -> Account (child): Appointments are booked for students\n- ServiceAppointment -> ServiceTerritory (lookup): Appointments are assigned to a service territory\n- ServiceAppointment -> ServiceResource (lookup): Appointments are assigned to a staff member\n- ServiceResource -> ServiceTerritory (lookup): Resources are assigned to service territories\n- ServiceResource -> ServiceAppointment (parent): Resources receive appointment assignments\n- ServiceTerritory -> ServiceResource (parent): Territories have assigned service resources\n- ServiceTerritory -> ServiceAppointment (parent): Appointments are booked within territories\n- DataStream -> IdentityResolutionRuleset (lookup): Data streams feed into identity resolution rulesets\n- IdentityResolutionRuleset -> MatchRule (parent): Rulesets contain matching rules\n- MatchRule -> IdentityResolutionRuleset (child): Match rules belong to a ruleset\n- UnifiedIndividual -> Account (lookup): Unified individuals map to person accounts\n\n## Cross-Domain Connections\n- Recruitment <-> Admissions: Qualified prospects move to applications\n- Recruitment <-> Student Records: Prospect data creates person records\n- Recruitment <-> Agentforce: AI recruitment agent automates outreach\n- Recruitment <-> Experience Cloud: Prospect portal for inquiry and events\n- Recruitment <-> Education Analytics: Recruitment funnel dashboards\n- Admissions <-> Student Records: Applicant data stored on person records\n- Admissions <-> Enrollment: Admitted students enroll in programs\n- Admissions <-> Student Financials: Application fees and financial aid packaging\n- Admissions <-> Agentforce: AI agent answers applicant questions\n- Admissions <-> Experience Cloud: Applicant portal for status tracking\n- Academic Operations <-> Enrollment: Programs and courses define what students enroll in\n- Academic Operations <-> Student Records: Transfer credits link to student education history\n- Academic Operations <-> Student Financials: Course structure drives tuition calculation\n- Academic Operations <-> Student Success: Learning objectives tie to competency tracking\n- Enrollment <-> Student Records: Enrollment records link to person accounts\n- Enrollment <-> Student Success: Enrollment progress feeds student success tracking\n- Enrollment <-> Student Financials: Course registration triggers fee calculation\n- Enrollment <-> Appointments: Registration may require advising appointments\n- Student Records <-> Student Success: Competencies and traits linked to person\n- Student Records <-> Student Financials: Financial accounts linked to person records\n- Student Records <-> Mentoring: Mentor/mentee profiles reference person records\n- Student Records <-> Alumni & Advancement: Alumni status tracked on person records\n- Student Records <-> Appointments: Appointments reference student records\n- Student Records <-> Data 360: Identity resolution unifies duplicate person records\n- Student Success <-> Mentoring: Mentoring outcomes feed into success tracking\n- Student Success <-> Appointments: Advising appointments support interventions\n- Student Success <-> Agentforce: AI advising agent surfaces at-risk students\n- Student Financials <-> Alumni & Advancement: Scholarship funds connect to advancement\n- Student Financials <-> Agentforce: Financial aid agent answers billing questions\n- Student Financials <-> Experience Cloud: Student financial self-service portal\n- Student Financials <-> Education Analytics: Financial health dashboards\n- Mentoring <-> Appointments: Mentoring sessions scheduled as appointments\n- Alumni & Advancement <-> Agentforce: Alumni engagement agent manages outreach\n- Alumni & Advancement <-> Experience Cloud: Alumni portal for giving and volunteering\n- Alumni & Advancement <-> Education Analytics: Advancement dashboards and giving reports\n- Education Analytics <-> Agentforce: Agent performance monitoring\n\n## Data Flows\n### Recruitment\n1. Prospect submits inquiry or attends recruitment event\n2. Lead record is created and assigned to a recruitment counselor\n3. Counselor nurtures prospect through targeted campaigns\n4. AI recruitment agent automates personalized outreach\n5. Qualified prospect proceeds to formal application submission\n### Admissions\n1. Applicant submits application with required documents\n2. Document checklist tracks receipt and verification of materials\n3. Application is routed to reviewers based on program and criteria\n4. Reviewers score and recommend using structured rubrics\n5. Admissions committee renders final decision\n6. Decision is communicated and applicant responds with intent to enroll\n### Academic Operations\n1. Academic departments define programs with degree requirements\n2. Courses are created in the catalog with prerequisites and credit values\n3. Course offerings are scheduled for specific terms with instructors\n4. Equivalency rules are established for transfer credit evaluation\n5. Academic calendar sets registration windows and deadlines\n### Enrollment\n1. Admitted student is enrolled in a degree program\n2. Student registers for course offerings each term\n3. System enforces prerequisites, capacity limits, and time conflicts\n4. Grades are recorded and achievements accumulate\n5. Learning plans track progress toward degree completion\n### Student Records\n1. Person account is created during recruitment or application\n2. Contact points, relationships, and demographics are populated\n3. Education history and test scores are added for admissions evaluation\n4. Record is enriched throughout the student lifecycle\n5. Post-graduation data tracks alumni employment and engagement\n### Student Success\n1. Student's competencies, traits, and affinities are assessed and recorded\n2. Advisor is assigned based on program, year, and caseload\n3. Early alert system monitors academic performance and engagement\n4. Alerts trigger interventions and advising sessions\n5. Career development planning guides students toward post-graduation goals\n### Student Financials\n1. Institution defines fee products with pricing attributes\n2. Price books establish term-specific fee amounts\n3. Student registers for courses, triggering order generation\n4. Pricing rules evaluate student attributes to calculate charges\n5. Financial aid is applied and payment plans are created\n6. Student account balance is updated with net amount due\n### Mentoring\n1. Program administrator defines mentoring program and benefits\n2. Mentors and mentees create profiles with matching-relevant information\n3. AI matching engine compares profiles and suggests optimal pairings\n4. Administrator reviews and finalizes mentor-mentee assignments\n5. Benefits are assigned and progress is tracked throughout the relationship\n### Alumni & Advancement\n1. Graduate transitions to alumni status on person record\n2. Alumni engagement activities are tracked and scored\n3. Fundraising campaigns target segmented alumni populations\n4. Gifts and pledges are recorded and acknowledged\n5. Volunteer activities are coordinated and recognized\n### Appointments\n1. Staff configures availability and service territories\n2. Student browses available slots by department and topic\n3. Appointment is booked with confirmation and calendar invite\n4. Walk-in students join the waitlist with estimated wait time\n5. Virtual meeting link is generated for remote appointments\n### Education Analytics\n1. Data from recruitment, enrollment, success, and financial systems flows into analytics\n2. Pre-built dashboards aggregate metrics into role-specific views\n3. Directors review institutional KPIs and trend indicators\n4. Department heads drill into program-level and cohort-level detail\n5. Custom reports address ad-hoc institutional research questions\n### Agentforce\n1. Agent is configured with education-specific topics and guardrails\n2. Student or prospect initiates conversation through portal or messaging\n3. Agent accesses relevant records to provide personalized responses\n4. Complex inquiries are escalated to human staff with full context\n5. Agent performance metrics feed into analytics dashboards\n### Experience Cloud\n1. Portal is configured with role-based page layouts and permissions\n2. Student, applicant, or alumni authenticates and accesses personalized dashboard\n3. Self-service actions trigger backend processes in Education Cloud\n4. Status updates and notifications are pushed back to the portal\n5. Mobile-responsive design ensures access across all devices\n### Data 360\n1. Source systems are connected via data streams with extraction schedules\n2. Raw data is mapped and transformed to the Education Cloud schema\n3. Identity resolution detects duplicates across source systems\n4. Matched records are merged into unified individual records\n5. Unified data feeds all Education Cloud domains through person accounts\n\n## Links\nUse these URLs when mentioning domains or components:\n- [Recruitment](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/recruitment)\n- [Admissions](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/admissions)\n- [Academic Operations](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/academics)\n- [Enrollment](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/enrollment)\n- [Student Records](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/records)\n- [Student Success](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/success)\n- [Student Financials](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/financials)\n- [Mentoring](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/mentoring)\n- [Alumni & Advancement](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/alumni)\n- [Appointments](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/appointments)\n- [Education Analytics](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/analytics)\n- [Agentforce](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/agentforce)\n- [Experience Cloud](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/experience)\n- [Data 360](https://epugach.github.io/product-explorer/educationcloud/#/data360)\n";
